\section{Reduction in the general case}
\label{sec.reduction_general}

We now generalize our reduction method and allow $|w\rangle$ to be
anywhere in the tree. We denote the level on which the marked site
is by $l$ (and $n$ is the total number of levels, as before). We
will see below that we can reduce the full system to one of size less
than $n^{2}=(\log N)^{2}$ in a way similar to what has been done
in Sec.~\ref{sec.red_tree}. Eq.~\eqref{eq.reducedHamiltonian}
for the Hamiltonian in the reduced system, ${\overline{{H}}}=VHV^{+}$, is
still valid and useful, but the necessary conditions are not constructive
-- they do not show how to find the matrix $V$. We use the following
intuitive argument (as has been done, for instance, in Ref.~\cite{PhysRevA.92.032320}):
We can group together sites that are indistinguishable in the sense
that (a) their positions in the graph are qualitatively the same,
and (b) their positions relative to $|w\rangle$ are the same. For
example, for grouping sites together it is certainly necessary
that they (a) have the same degree, and (b) have the same distance
from $|w\rangle$.

